<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<section xml:id="inv-5-11">
  <title>Investigation 5.11: Running Out of Time (cont.)</title>

  <exercises xml:id="exercises5-11" hidden-label="yes">
    <title>The Study</title>

    <p>This investigation uses a randomization (shuffle) test for regression slope significance, conditioning on observed data.</p>

    <exercise xml:id="inv5-11-a" label="I5.11.a"><title>Prepare Data</title><statement><p>(a) Load race data, remove outlier, and confirm regression equation.</p></statement><response/><solution><p>Regression setup/output values should match the previous investigation after removing the same outlier.</p></solution></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-11-b" label="I5.11.b"><title>Single Shuffle</title><statement><p>(b) Shuffle y-values once and compare resulting regression line strength to observed.</p></statement><response/><solution><p>The slope will most likely be smaller than observed (as well the correlation coefficient, indicating a weaker association).</p></solution></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-11-c" label="I5.11.c"><title>Repeated Shuffles</title><statement><p>(c) Shuffle repeatedly and describe emerging line patterns.</p></statement><response/><solution><p>You should get a negative association about half the time, but probably never one as extreme as the observed slope (red line).</p></solution></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-11-d" label="I5.11.d"><title>Null Slope Distribution</title><statement><p>(d) Draw many shuffles and describe null distribution of slopes; compare to Investigation 5.10 sampling approach.</p></statement><response/><solution><p>Example results: The shape is rather symmetric, centered around zero, with a standard deviation of about 0.03. This is similar to what we saw in Investigation 5.10.</p></solution></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-11-e" label="I5.11.e"><title>Empirical p-value</title><statement><p>(e) Estimate p-value by counting shuffled slopes as/extremer than observed.</p></statement><response/><solution><p>Example results: None of the simulated slopes was as extreme as the observed sample slope.</p></solution></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-11-f" label="I5.11.f"><title>Standardize Observed Slope</title><statement><p>(f) Standardize observed slope using shuffled SD.</p></statement><response/><solution><p>If we standardize, we again get something like <m>(0.14-0)/.03\approx 4.67</m>.</p><p>Using an observed t statistic of 4.49, we are again on the right edge of the distribution.</p></solution></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-11-g" label="I5.11.g"><title>t-statistic Comparison</title><statement><p>(g) Compare shuffled t-based p-value with Investigation 5.10 result.</p></statement><response/><solution><p>The results are very similar to the previous investigation.</p></solution></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-11-h" label="I5.11.h"><title>Overlay t Distribution</title><statement><p>(h) Assess t-distribution overlay fit for shuffled t-statistics.</p></statement><response/><solution><p>The <m>t</m>-distribution appears to be a good model for this randomization distribution.</p></solution></exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="inv5-11-i" label="I5.11.i"><title>Regression Table Comparison</title><statement><p>(i) Compare applet regression-table SE to shuffled SD behavior.</p></statement><response/><solution><p>the two simulation models agree because we are getting a similar standard deviation of the sample/shuffled slopes. If the association had been stronger, this would not necessarily be the case. Also keep in mind the distinction between strength of evidence (which is strong here because the sample size is rather larger) and strength of association. This regression model explains less than 8% of the variability in finishing times.</p></solution></exercise>

    <assemblage>
      <title>Discussion</title>
      <p>Random sampling and random shuffling usually yield similar inferential conclusions, but shuffling conditions on observed x and y values and can be more flexible when population-model assumptions are uncertain.</p>
    </assemblage>

    <exercise xml:id="inv5-11-practice" label="I5.11.practice"><title>Practice Problem 5.11</title><statement><p>Repeat this comparison using height and foot-length data from Investigation 5.8.</p></statement><response/></exercise>
  </exercises>
</section>
